6. Machine Learning Model

The Linear Regression algorithm was selected for this project because it is simple, efficient, and suitable for regression problems.

The dataset was divided into:

Training Data: 80%
Testing Data: 20%

The model was trained using the training dataset and tested on unseen data.

7. Model Performance

The model performance was evaluated using three standard regression metrics.

Mean Absolute Error (MAE)

1.57

The average prediction error is approximately 1.57 lakhs.

Mean Squared Error (MSE)

6.83

This metric measures the average squared prediction error.

R² Score

0.735 (73.5%)

The model explains approximately 73.5% of the variation in car prices, indicating good predictive performance for a basic Linear Regression model.

8. Key Findings
Present Price has the strongest influence on Selling Price.
Newer cars generally have higher selling prices.
Cars with fewer kilometers driven tend to have better resale values.
Fuel type and transmission also affect selling price.
The Linear Regression model achieved satisfactory prediction accuracy.
9. Conclusion

This project successfully developed a machine learning model to predict car selling prices using Linear Regression. The dataset was cleaned, analyzed, and visualized before model training. The evaluation results show that the model provides reasonably accurate predictions with an R² score of 0.735. This project demonstrates how machine learning techniques can be applied to real-world price prediction problems and can be further improved by using advanced algorithms such as Random Forest or XGBoost.

